english:
  title: Preface to the Assembly of Elders of the Eastern Land
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    During the Huichang era of Tang, when Bai Juyi retired from his position as Tutor to the Crown Prince and dwelt in Luoyang, he gathered six virtuous and long-lived men to feast at his residence on Lüdao Lane. This became known as the Assembly Honoring Age and Virtue. Among them were Hu Gao, former Military Commander of Huaizhou, aged eighty-nine; Ji Min, retired Chief of the Palace Guard, aged eighty-six; Zheng Ju, former Commander of the Dragon and Tiger Army, aged eighty-four; Liu Zhen, former Prefect of Cizhou; Lu Zhen, former Censor, both aged eighty-two; and Zhang Hun, former Prefect of Yongzhou, who with Bai Juyi shared the same age of seventy-four. Though the Secret Ministry Supervisor Di Jianmo and the Henan Governor Lu Zhen were under seventy, they participated though not counted among the primary members. Bai Juyi immortalized this gathering in verse, and posterity came to call it the Assembly of Nine Elders of Luoyang.

    When Wen Luogong served as Military Commissioner of Luoyang during the Yuanfeng era of Song, he too made covenant with elder worthies to form the Assembly of Genuine Simplicity, commissioning their portraits to be painted at the Miaojue Monastery. Thirteen members gathered: Fu Hanpublic Bi, aged seventy-nine; Wen Luogong Yanbuo and Advisor Xi Ruyan, aged seventy-seven; Advisor Wang Shanggong, aged seventy-six; Grand Keeper Zhao Bing, Secret Ministry Director Liu Ji, and Defense Commander Feng Xingji, all aged seventy-five; Awaiting-Duty Chu Jianzhong, aged seventy-three; Advisor Wang Tianyan, aged seventy-two; Palace Counselor Wang Gongchen, aged seventy-one; Grand Secretary Zhang Wen and Scholar Zhang Shou, both aged seventy; and only Sima Wenggong at sixty-four, yet included by precedent of Lu Zhen and Di Jianmo. Sima composed the preface for that assembly.

    Our Eastern Land, having enjoyed four centuries of peace, produced worthy men and refined culture that rivaled the Central Realm. When the Divine King entered the Year of the Horse, Minister Choe Jeong'an finally retired from office and established the Hall of Twin Illuminations in Yeongchangri. In the Year of the Boar, he gathered elder statesmen who had withdrawn from service and spent their days in poetry, wine, zither, and chess. Admirers of such things commissioned a painting of the Assembly of Eastern Elders. Cho Tong also recorded this moment with enthusiasm. By the Year of the Monkey, Minister Jeong'an's younger brother, the Cultivated Minister Choe, having reached seventy, submitted his resignation to retire, and thus joined this gathering. His portrait was added to the scroll. Park Inseok recorded this addition.

    The first of these nine was Grand Keeper of Carriage Zhang Jamouk, Keeper of the Precious Text Pavilion and Scholar-in-Waiting, retired, aged seventy-eight. The second was Chancellor Choe Dang, Grand Councilor of State and Scholar of the Assembly for Worthy Government, retired, aged seventy-seven. The third was Minister Yi Junchangg, Senior Minister of the Right, retired, of the same age as Chancellor Choe. The fourth was Judge of the Secret Archives and Hanlin Scholar Baek Gwangsin, retired, aged seventy-four. The fifth was Chief of Rites and Tutor to the Crown Prince Gao Yingzhong, retired, of the same age as Baek Gwangsin. The sixth was Minister Yi Sechang, Senior Minister of the Right and Scholar of the Precious Text Pavilion, retired, aged seventy-one. The seventh was Minister of Revenue Hyun Deoksu, retired, of the same age as Minister Yi. The eighth was Grand Tutor and Chancellor Choe Seon, Scholar of the Hall of Refined Culture, retired, aged sixty-nine. The ninth was Military Equipment Supervisor Cho Tong, aged sixty-four. In total, nine worthy men.

    At that time, Li Meishou, a Hanlin Scholar, following the precedent of Lu Zhen, Di Jianmo, and Sima Wenggong, mingled freely among these elders and composed more than a hundred poems and writings, vividly capturing the beauty of that gathering. Thus the "Collection of the Hall of Twin Illuminations" was transmitted to the scholarly community.

    Now, with the Yuan Dynasty upholding supreme benevolence and sacred virtue to nurture all under heaven, and our kingdom foremost in offering allegiance, generation after generation has received the blessings of that bond. Our princes steadfastly uphold the laws of their investiture; ruler and ruled rejoice together; no whisper of alarm troubles our borders; harvests abound year after year. Truly this is an age of brilliant peace that comes once in a thousand years. At this very time, the Crown itself cultivates its essence and dedicates itself to learning, favoring the worthy and nurturing goodness. Below it, great princes and sage ministers serve as the kingdom's foundation. All have reached the age of fullness and, withdrawing from service, dwell in ease and share in security and honor. Though this gathering arises from circumstance, its elegant discourse becomes a model for the age. How could such men, whose integrity endured their whole lives and whose renown shines forth, fail to inspire the admiration of all three Han territories?

    One day, the Venerable Master of the Eastern Study summoned me, a mere junior scholar of no standing, and spoke thus: "Recently our elders have gathered, wishing to revive the teachings of the Luoyang Society and the Hall of Twin Illuminations. Will you compose a preface for them?" I demurred, saying my youth and low station rendered me unfit to accept such responsibility. The Master smiled and replied: "When Li Meishou was drawn into the circle of the Hall of Twin Illuminations, was it decided by age or rank? You must not refuse." Yielding to his insistence, I withdrew to reflect. Alas, the noble deeds and sacred virtue of these great ministers have been inscribed upon the realm and are known to all—far beyond what my humble learning could illuminate. Yet the history of such assemblies, past and present, demands to be recorded. Therefore, I have undertaken to set down this account.
  footnotes:
    - The Assembly of Nine Elders of Luoyang was a celebrated gathering immortalized in Chinese literary tradition by the poet Bai Juyi during the Tang Dynasty.
    - The Hall of Twin Illuminations (雙明齋) refers to the Korean counterpart assembly established by Minister Choe Jeong'an, modeled after the earlier Chinese precedent.
    - The three Han territories (三韓) traditionally refer to ancient Korean kingdoms and is used here to evoke the broader Korean realm.
